---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
const lang = 'en' as const;

const jsonLd = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Person",
    "@id": "https://curfee.com/#founder",
    "name": "Philipp Höllinger",
    "jobTitle": "Software Architect",
    "url": "https://curfee.com/about",
    "worksFor": { "@id": "https://curfee.com/#organization" },
    "address": { "@type": "PostalAddress", "addressLocality": "Salzburg", "addressCountry": "AT" },
    "sameAs": ["https://www.linkedin.com/in/phoellinger"]
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
    "itemListElement": [
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://curfee.com/en/" },
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "About", "item": "https://curfee.com/en/about" }
    ]
  }
];
---

<Layout
  ui={{
    nav: { services: "Services", about: "About", faq: "FAQ", cta: "Contact" },
    serviceNames: { diagnosis: "Diagnosis", guidance: "Guidance", sparring: "Sparring" },
    footer: { notice: "Legal Notice", privacy: "Privacy Policy", cookies: "Cookie Policy", copyright: "All rights reserved." },
    consent: { message: "This website uses cookies for usage analysis.", learnMore: "Learn more", accept: "Accept", decline: "Decline" },
    meta: { defaultDescription: "Philipp Höllinger, software architect from Salzburg. I help organizations build lasting structure in their systems. Diagnosis, Guidance, Sparring.", orgDescription: "Building lasting structure in systems. Diagnosis, Guidance, Sparring.", jobTitle: "Software Architect" },
  }}
  title="About — Curfee | Philipp Höllinger, Software Architect"
  description="Philipp Höllinger, software architect from Salzburg. An obsession with the things that go unnoticed. The details that shape the future of a system."
  canonicalPath="/en/about"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
  lang={lang}
  dateModified="2026-03-30"
>

  <section class="mb-20 max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
    <picture><source srcset="/assets/profile.webp" type="image/webp" /><img src="/assets/profile.png" alt="Philipp Höllinger" class="w-[160px] h-[200px] object-cover object-top rounded-md mb-8" loading="lazy" /></picture>
    <h1 class="text-display-small md:text-display-medium text-ink-primary mb-8">Philipp Höllinger</h1>
    <div class="space-y-6 text-body-large text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
      <p>I anchor decisions in structure — across software, tools, and organizations. My career began in logistics — coordinating processes between goods, people, and procedures. From there, I moved into software development and finally into architecture: automotive industry, public sector, software consulting.</p>
      <p>What I observed: the more tools, processes, and people interact with each other, the more important it becomes that decisions last and are anchored in structure — not held in individual minds, not enforced through discipline — especially as teams grow, people change, and requirements shift.</p>
      <p>Structure always exists. The question is whether it was intentionally designed — or simply emerged because no one was responsible for it. Responsibility often doesn't arise from a decision, but by accident — someone grows into a role without truly being in charge, and often without the decision-making authority or the expertise it requires. The role that would need to be accountable for structural quality doesn't exist in most projects — and its absence goes unnoticed until the consequences surface.</p>
      <p>What drives me: an obsession with the things that go unnoticed. The details that shape the future of a system.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-20 max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
    <h2 class="text-headline-large md:text-display-small text-ink-primary mb-8">What I've done</h2>
    <div class="space-y-10">
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-title-large text-ink-primary mb-3">Justice</h3>
        <p class="text-body-large text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">A booking system that didn't prevent errors — it enabled them. No transactional integrity, no validation rules, no database constraints. Rooms were double-booked, bookings in the past were possible, conflicting bookings went unchecked. The root cause wasn't poor development — it was the absence of structure that would have prevented these errors by design. I put that structure in place. Duplicate entries disappeared, performance improved by 20% — and for the first time, people could rely on a booked room actually being available for them.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-title-large text-ink-primary mb-3">Public Administration</h3>
        <p class="text-body-large text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">The EU Single Digital Gateway required administrative information to be available in a structured, multilingual, and machine-readable format — in German and English for EU citizens, crawlable for EU infrastructure. I designed a system that lets editors create and update content, tag it with metadata, and publish it automatically. A structured translation workflow was integrated — the first application of its kind in the region.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-title-large text-ink-primary mb-3">Tourism & Leisure</h3>
        <p class="text-body-large text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">For seven years, one student per region spent three months each summer reading emails and manually entering events. Five regions, five students, every year. The root cause wasn't a staffing problem. There was no standardized input format, no shared foundation. I designed a form that event organizers fill out themselves, an automated import that loads the data daily, and an approval mechanism for review and editing. What used to be a summer job is now a click.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-20 max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
    <h2 class="text-headline-large md:text-display-small text-ink-primary mb-8">What I stand for</h2>
    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-6">
        <span class="text-headline-large md:text-display-small text-brand-primary/50 font-display flex-shrink-0 w-10 md:w-14 select-none leading-none">1</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-title-large text-ink-primary mb-1">Root cause over symptom</h3>
          <p class="text-body-large text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">Real solutions start with understanding what is actually going on.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-6">
        <span class="text-headline-large md:text-display-small text-brand-primary/50 font-display flex-shrink-0 w-10 md:w-14 select-none leading-none">2</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-title-large text-ink-primary mb-1">Structure over discipline</h3>
          <p class="text-body-large text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">What holds must be embedded in the system, not in individual behavior.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-6">
        <span class="text-headline-large md:text-display-small text-brand-primary/50 font-display flex-shrink-0 w-10 md:w-14 select-none leading-none">3</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-title-large text-ink-primary mb-1">Lasting over workaround</h3>
          <p class="text-body-large text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">What I build outlasts people and technologies.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-20 max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
    <h2 class="text-headline-large md:text-display-small text-ink-primary mb-8">How I work</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6 text-body-large text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
      <p>I don't deliver quick answers — I deliver the right one.</p>
      <p>I approach every system without assumptions about where the root cause lies — I know the problem, but not where its root cause lies. Whether it's a software architecture, a tool landscape, a process, or an organizational structure — I always start high-level: what interacts with the problem, what connects to what, what influences what. Only when the full picture is clear do I go deeper.</p>
      <p>That also means: I look at more than seems necessary at first glance. Because root causes rarely sit where the symptom is visible.</p>
      <p>Once the root cause is found, I strip everything back to what matters. What lies between symptom and root cause and contributes nothing to the solution falls away. What remains gets embedded in a structure that anchors decisions, dependencies, and connections — and holds independently of me.</p>
      <p>Depending on the problem, I work alone or involve the team. For diagnosis, I decide based on the situation. For guidance, the team is always part of the process — because I don't implement; I design the structure and guide the execution.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-20 max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
    <h2 class="text-headline-large md:text-display-small text-ink-primary mb-12">Five principles</h2>
    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div class="flex items-start gap-6 min-h-[3.5rem]">
        <span class="text-display-small text-brand-primary font-display leading-none w-12 flex-shrink-0 text-center">C</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-title-large text-ink-primary mb-1"><span class="text-brand-primary">C</span>uriosity</h3>
          <p class="text-body-large text-ink-muted">I approach every system without assumptions and examine what is actually there.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex items-start gap-6 min-h-[3.5rem]">
        <span class="text-display-small text-brand-primary font-display leading-none w-12 flex-shrink-0 text-center">U</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-title-large text-ink-primary mb-1"><span class="text-brand-primary">U</span>nderstanding</h3>
          <p class="text-body-large text-ink-muted">I dig into the existing structures, dependencies, and connections.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex items-start gap-6 min-h-[3.5rem]">
        <span class="text-display-small text-brand-primary font-display leading-none w-12 flex-shrink-0 text-center">R</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-title-large text-ink-primary mb-1"><span class="text-brand-primary">R</span>eflection</h3>
          <p class="text-body-large text-ink-muted">I validate my findings from multiple directions until the full picture holds.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex items-start gap-6 min-h-[3.5rem]">
        <span class="text-display-small text-brand-primary font-display leading-none w-12 flex-shrink-0 text-center">F</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-title-large text-ink-primary mb-1"><span class="text-brand-primary">F</span>oresight</h3>
          <p class="text-body-large text-ink-muted">I assess what the system needs to deliver in the future — and what it takes to get there.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex items-start gap-6 min-h-[3.5rem]">
        <span class="text-display-small text-brand-primary font-display leading-none w-12 flex-shrink-0 text-center">EE</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-title-large text-ink-primary mb-1"><span class="text-brand-primary">E</span>ssence</h3>
          <p class="text-body-large text-ink-muted">I reduce to what truly matters.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
